cyclone.name: ETA
cyclone.current_location: about 80 miles NNW of the western tip of Cuba
cyclone.trajectory: Forecast to move slowly northward through the eastern Gulf of Mexico and approach the west-central Florida coast late Thursday
cyclone.expected_landfall_location: west-central Florida coast between Tampa Bay and the Big Bend (near/just north of Port Manatee)

weather_observation.watch_coast: Tropical-storm watch for the Cuban provinces of La Habana eastward to the Isle of Youth
weather_observation.impacted_coast: Entire west coast of Florida from the Keys northward to the Big Bend is inside the 5-day cone and in the tropical-storm wind probability field
weather_observation.wind: Tropical-storm-force gusts (35–45 kt) are possible late Wednesday night through Thursday as the center nears the port; sustained winds most likely remain below gale force until within 24 h of closest approach.
weather_observation.storm_surge: Depending on exact track, a surge of 2–4 ft above ground level is possible in Tampa Bay and the lower bay near Port Manatee, especially with onshore southerly flow Thursday.
weather_observation.rainfall: Bands of heavy rain could bring 3–5 inches with localized higher totals over 6 inches, producing flash-flood potential around the port.
weather_observation.other_hazards: Dangerous surf and rip currents beginning mid-week; brief tornadoes in outer rainbands cannot be ruled out.
